WEBVTT

00:06.466 --> 00:09.010
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

01:16.119 --> 01:17.412
MACKENZIE: <i>Here's where we are.</i>

01:17.495 --> 01:19.956
<i>August 24 of last year</i>
<i>we had a guest on a panel</i>

01:20.039 --> 01:22.167
<i>about drones named Cyrus West,</i>

01:22.250 --> 01:25.587
<i>a retired Air Force captain</i>
<i>who now teaches at the Maxwell School.</i>

01:25.670 --> 01:29.048
When the panel was done,
Captain West gave Jerry a tip

01:29.132 --> 01:31.593
about a black op with the codename Genoa.

01:31.676 --> 01:33.636
What did he tell you about Genoa?

01:33.720 --> 01:36.014
He told me that in March 2009, two Marines

01:36.097 --> 01:38.266
were separated from
their unit in the Hindu Kush.

01:38.349 --> 01:41.853
Intelligence told us
that they were captured by Taliban fighters,

01:41.936 --> 01:45.064
taken across the border into Pakistan,
held in a small village,

01:45.148 --> 01:46.691
and in a matter of a few hours

01:46.775 --> 01:49.569
they were gonna be sold
to al-Qaeda and publically beheaded.

01:49.652 --> 01:52.447
MACKENZIE: A MARSOC unit was
deployed to attempt an extraction.

01:52.530 --> 01:56.409
Two MH-60s, Black Hawks,
came in with 15 MARSOCs apiece.

01:56.493 --> 01:59.245
The first unit was overrun by the enemy
and trapped behind cover.

01:59.329 --> 02:02.123
- They were wearing MOPP gear.
- Mission Oriented Protective Posture.

02:02.207 --> 02:03.708
The second unit, also in MOPP gear,

02:03.792 --> 02:06.044
came in and successfully
extracted the prisoners

02:06.127 --> 02:07.796
as well as the first MARSOC unit.

02:07.879 --> 02:10.423
- How?
- By dropping sarin gas on the village.

02:18.306 --> 02:19.641
How would the prisoners have survived?

02:19.724 --> 02:21.351
We hit them with atropine
and dragged them onto the helos.

02:21.434 --> 02:23.812
- Everyone else was wearing MOPP gear.
- Everyone but the civilians.

02:23.895 --> 02:26.856
MACKENZIE: That was Cyrus West's story
and that was last August.

02:26.940 --> 02:30.485
Jerry then tracked down
a retired gunnery sergeant, Eric Sweeney.

02:30.568 --> 02:32.028
Jerry and I met with Sergeant Sweeney

02:32.111 --> 02:36.658
and the full transcript of that meeting
begins on page four in your binders.

02:36.741 --> 02:38.535
Sweeney describes rehearsals
for the mission...

02:38.618 --> 02:40.995
- In MOPP gear.
- ...and then describes the mission itself.

02:41.120 --> 02:44.290
He witnesses blinding smoke
and women and children

02:44.374 --> 02:45.834
with boils and burns on their faces.

02:45.917 --> 02:47.877
Back on the helicopter
he asks another member of his crew

02:47.961 --> 02:50.755
what that was all about
and he's told it was sarin.

02:50.839 --> 02:52.841
MACKENZIE: Jerry put a team together
to track down other members

02:52.924 --> 02:55.510
of the crew and any ground support,
but no one was talking.

02:55.593 --> 02:58.096
Neal then did a search
of any tweets from the area

02:58.179 --> 03:00.932
sent around March '09
and came up with Hamni8.

03:01.099 --> 03:03.059
The tweets from Hamni8
would seem to be describing

03:03.142 --> 03:06.062
what we'd heard
from Sergeant Sweeney and from Cyrus West.

03:06.145 --> 03:07.397
"Helicopters. Grenades."

03:07.480 --> 03:09.649
Then a moment later,
"Men in gas masks. Machine guns."

03:09.732 --> 03:12.819
A moment later, "Burning."
Then, "Americans. White smoke."

03:12.902 --> 03:15.488
Then, "Two helicopters.
No markings on them, but they're American."

03:15.572 --> 03:17.866
It's 32 minutes before the next tweet.

03:17.949 --> 03:19.617
"I think everyone's dead."

03:19.742 --> 03:22.745
MACKENZIE: We believe the reason for
the 32-minute gap is frequency hopping.

03:22.829 --> 03:24.581
We'd have jammed
the radio frequencies cell phones use.

03:24.664 --> 03:27.292
West is one, Sweeney is two, Hamni8 is three.

03:27.375 --> 03:30.628
Four is a humanitarian report
from a guy named Leon Deit.

03:30.712 --> 03:34.007
Deit was in the region working for an NGO

03:34.090 --> 03:38.303
and traveled to the site of the extraction
on verbal reports of a mass grave.

03:38.386 --> 03:41.180
The eyewitness accounts
are consistent with the use of sarin gas.

03:41.264 --> 03:44.225
And as you can see, the report includes

03:44.309 --> 03:45.685
pictures of the victims.

03:45.768 --> 03:49.230
Five is a confidential source
who confirmed the story

03:49.314 --> 03:52.108
and provided a copy
of the munitions manifest.

03:52.191 --> 03:55.612
The manifest included this item, MX-76.

03:55.695 --> 03:59.824
MX-76 doesn't exist.
It's a euphemism for classified material.

03:59.908 --> 04:02.869
We believe it's the sarin canisters.

04:02.952 --> 04:04.746
MACKENZIE: The five of us
as well as some other staffers

04:04.829 --> 04:06.873
have had a role in putting this together so far.

04:06.956 --> 04:09.250
We've purposely kept
a number of people out of the loop

04:09.334 --> 04:12.170
including Will for fresh eyes.

04:12.253 --> 04:14.297
Are there any questions?

04:21.512 --> 04:23.473
- Sarin gas?
- MACKENZIE: I don't believe it, either.

04:23.556 --> 04:27.060
I also don't believe in Santa Claus,
but if I saw eight reindeer take flight...

04:27.143 --> 04:28.770
To be clear, you haven't seen eight reindeer.

04:28.853 --> 04:30.855
You've talked to someone
who says he's seen eight reindeer.

04:30.939 --> 04:32.899
And we have someone
who's tweeted about the reindeer

04:32.982 --> 04:35.777
and a third witness
who's interviewed victims of the reindeer

04:35.860 --> 04:38.613
and a highly-placed
confidential source who's confirmed

04:38.696 --> 04:41.157
that in this place at that time, reindeer flew.

04:41.240 --> 04:44.035
It couldn't matter less,
but Santa Claus has nine reindeer.

04:44.118 --> 04:45.620
- Rudolph.
- Mac, I don't think...

04:45.703 --> 04:47.372
- Dasher, Dancer.
- Vixen, Blitzen.

04:47.455 --> 04:49.165
- How many was that?
- It really doesn't matter.

04:49.248 --> 04:50.625
- You believe we used sarin?
- Yes.

04:50.708 --> 04:52.043
- On civilians?
- Yes.

04:52.126 --> 04:53.628
- Dasher, Dancer, Prancer.
- What are you doing?

04:53.711 --> 04:55.171
Well, I'm digesting what I just heard.

04:55.254 --> 04:56.965
I'm doing a fact check
on the number of reindeer.

04:57.048 --> 04:59.300
Dasher, Dancer, Prancer,
Comet, Blitzen, Cupid,

04:59.384 --> 05:01.803
Donner, Vixen, and somebody else.

05:01.886 --> 05:02.971
- Rudolph.
- Thank you.

05:03.054 --> 05:04.305
- Wait, how many was that?
- Start again.

05:04.389 --> 05:06.140
No. Do we even have sarin gas?

05:06.224 --> 05:09.143
We aren't supposed to.
It was supposed to be destroyed by 2007

05:09.227 --> 05:10.770
according to the
Chemical Weapons Convention.

05:10.853 --> 05:12.939
But it wasn't. We still have it.
The DOD confirms that.

05:13.022 --> 05:14.607
We may have it, but we've never used it.

05:14.691 --> 05:19.028
We didn't use it in World War II,
Korea, Vietnam, the first Gulf War,

05:19.112 --> 05:20.989
and we were fighting people that did have...

05:21.072 --> 05:22.740
Those all happened before 9/11.

05:24.575 --> 05:27.161
We torture people now.
We kidnap them, wiretap them...

05:27.245 --> 05:30.665
- Drop deadly gas on civilians?
- It happened, Jim.

05:30.748 --> 05:32.709
This is the one we know about.

05:32.792 --> 05:34.919
- The original tip came from Cyrus West?
- MACKENZIE: I know, but...

05:35.003 --> 05:38.172
- JIM: He's not reliable.
- His crime was not being good on television.

05:38.256 --> 05:40.508
But he led us to Eric Sweeney, so who cares?

05:40.591 --> 05:41.592
What about the Marines who were rescued?

05:41.676 --> 05:42.760
MACKENZIE: We don't know their names

05:42.844 --> 05:45.096
and they wouldn't have been
in a good position to know what happened.

05:45.179 --> 05:47.056
Sweeney says they were in a hole
in back of one of the houses.

05:47.140 --> 05:48.182
And then they were exposed to the gas.

05:48.266 --> 05:49.851
They would have known
if they were hit with an atropine.

05:49.934 --> 05:51.686
Probably, but it doesn't matter.
We don't know who they are

05:51.769 --> 05:52.854
and we've been looking for seven months.

05:52.937 --> 05:55.481
We have 30 names and here they are.

05:55.565 --> 05:57.275
These were given to us by Sweeney.

05:57.358 --> 05:58.943
None of them is talking with the exception

05:59.027 --> 06:01.487
of Lance Corporal Herman Valenzuela
who's dead.

06:02.905 --> 06:04.866
It sounded like you said Herman Valenzuela,

06:04.949 --> 06:06.534
in spite of being dead, is talking.

06:06.617 --> 06:08.202
- I wasn't saying that.
- I was confused by that, too.

06:08.286 --> 06:10.496
Valenzuela was killed in action,
the other 29 aren't talking.

06:10.580 --> 06:12.081
What about Hamni8?
Have you tried to track him down?

06:12.165 --> 06:14.542
Yes, but he's gone.
We believe given his proximity to the raid

06:14.625 --> 06:15.877
that he was killed.

06:15.960 --> 06:17.837
Well, or that he couldn't pay for his cell plan.

06:18.129 --> 06:19.630
Those are two pretty different things.

06:19.714 --> 06:22.341
DON: Have we put boots on the ground to
see if there's any locals we can talk to?

06:22.425 --> 06:24.510
You can't send Americans in there
or anyone working for Americans.

06:24.594 --> 06:25.887
- A local fixer?
- MACKENZIE: It's much too dangerous.

06:25.970 --> 06:27.055
- What does Tapley say?
- JERRY: Who?

06:27.138 --> 06:29.015
Mike Tapley, our military analyst,

06:29.098 --> 06:30.683
who I don't know why
we didn't use him instead of West.

06:30.767 --> 06:32.351
'Cause I was producing the segment.

06:32.435 --> 06:34.437
Neither Mike nor our Pentagon correspondent
have been brought in.

06:34.520 --> 06:35.897
JERRY: The Pentagon
would go into shutdown.

06:35.980 --> 06:37.565
We'll ask for comment 24 hours before air.

06:39.650 --> 06:41.069
Before air?

06:41.152 --> 06:42.945
We're really talking about...

06:43.029 --> 06:45.782
Charlie, be the voice of reason.

06:45.865 --> 06:47.158
I think it happened

06:47.241 --> 06:49.994
and I think
we're two inches away from proving it.

06:50.078 --> 06:52.121
It's always 50-50 when you ask Charlie
to be the voice of reason.

06:52.205 --> 06:54.165
- Nobody's saying it's ready to air.
- I'm saying it's ready.

06:54.248 --> 06:55.291
CHARLIE: It certainly is not.

06:55.374 --> 06:59.337
And we can keep calling the names
on the list till St. Swithin's Day,

06:59.420 --> 07:02.090
but we have a better chance of
getting Herman Valenzuela to talk

07:02.173 --> 07:03.758
than any of the other 29.

07:03.841 --> 07:06.385
So we started looking
for someone not on the list.

07:06.469 --> 07:09.013
A flag officer who'd be
in a position to confirm the mission. Neal?

07:09.180 --> 07:11.099
We ran five separate searches
and cross-referenced

07:11.182 --> 07:13.059
the five search parameters
which were the following,

07:13.142 --> 07:16.938
recently retired generals who have attempted
to publish work that was heavily redacted,

07:17.021 --> 07:18.356
commanders who have served as head

07:18.439 --> 07:20.525
of the Marines Combat Logistics
and Munitions Element,

07:20.608 --> 07:23.569
generals who've taken
academic positions since retiring

07:23.653 --> 07:26.364
who've been critical
of the US stockpile of chemical weapons,

07:26.447 --> 07:29.117
and flag officers who were on active duty
when Genoa took place.

07:29.200 --> 07:30.660
When we think Genoa took place.

07:30.743 --> 07:33.955
There's one name that meets all five criteria.

07:34.038 --> 07:37.458
This is three-star Marine
General Stanislaus Stomtonovich.

07:37.542 --> 07:39.293
He was a munitions consultant at White Sands

07:39.377 --> 07:41.462
and an expert on the US
chemical weapons program.

07:41.546 --> 07:44.173
He retired six months
after Genoa and lives in Silver Spring.

07:44.257 --> 07:46.968
You're gonna call and ask him
if we dropped sarin gas on a small village?

07:47.051 --> 07:48.886
- No, we're going to his house.
- Charlie, God damn it.

07:48.970 --> 07:51.264
JERRY: He's already alerted
the Pentagon's Office of Public Affairs.

07:51.347 --> 07:54.308
He thinks we're coming about something else.
We're just getting in the vestibule.

07:54.392 --> 07:56.519
But eventually, you will ask him the question?

07:57.145 --> 07:59.063
Yeah.

07:59.564 --> 08:01.524
Do you understand
what we're accusing them of?

08:01.607 --> 08:03.860
We do, Jim, yeah.
And I think we're less concerned

08:03.943 --> 08:06.362
with what we're accusing
them of than we are with what they did.

08:06.445 --> 08:08.489
What you think they did,
which I still can't hardly believe

08:08.573 --> 08:10.491
my fucking ears we're even talking about.

08:10.575 --> 08:12.577
- What was the general's name?
- Stomtonovich.

08:12.660 --> 08:15.913
How are you gonna question Stomtonovich
without him knowing what you're asking?

08:15.997 --> 08:18.416
We're gonna ask him how chemical weapons
would be stored and deployed.

08:18.499 --> 08:20.501
- JIM: What's the cover story?
- Libya.

08:24.297 --> 08:26.174
You've been on this for seven months?

08:28.509 --> 08:30.136
Do you believe the story?

08:30.386 --> 08:31.512
(SIGHS)

08:31.888 --> 08:33.306
I don't know.

08:33.389 --> 08:35.308
Have we nailed down the number of reindeer?

08:36.017 --> 08:37.310
(RINGING)

08:39.770 --> 08:41.022
<i>I see you.</i>

08:41.105 --> 08:42.940
You seem really excited every time this works.

08:43.065 --> 08:45.985
Is it because you're seeing me
or is it because of the technology?

08:46.068 --> 08:47.987
<i>- The technology.</i>
- I get that.

08:48.070 --> 08:50.281
<i>But tomorrow night</i>
<i>it'll be because I'm seeing you.</i>

08:50.364 --> 08:52.575
I'll tell you why
you should be excited about tomorrow night.

08:52.658 --> 08:54.368
I got a suite at the Soho Grand.

08:54.452 --> 08:56.412
- It cost three years' salary.
<i>- I like you.</i>

08:56.495 --> 08:58.789
- That's such great news for me.
<i>- It really is.</i>

08:58.873 --> 09:02.460
So I'll pick you up at the event at 10:00.
I'll be out in the lobby. We'll go to dinner

09:02.543 --> 09:06.297
and then back to the hotel for,
you know, discretionary time.

09:06.547 --> 09:08.841
<i>- Speaking of dinner...</i>
- What's about to happen?

09:08.925 --> 09:10.927
<i>- Do you know Aubrey Lerner?</i>
- No.

09:11.010 --> 09:12.720
<i>- Her byline is AK.</i>
- I don't know her.

09:12.803 --> 09:14.305
<i>- AK Lerner.</i>
- I don't know her,

09:14.388 --> 09:16.599
but I feel like she's about to
be an obstacle in my path to...

09:16.682 --> 09:18.226
<i>- Discretionary time?</i>
- Yes.

09:18.309 --> 09:20.102
<i>No, she's been on the press plane</i>

09:20.186 --> 09:22.063
<i>for a couple of weeks</i>
<i>and she reports for mtvU.</i>

09:22.146 --> 09:24.899
It sounds like she'd have a really good time
staying home by herself tomorrow.

09:24.982 --> 09:26.484
I don't think you should rob her of that.

09:26.567 --> 09:28.277
<i>She stays at her parents' place</i>
<i>when she's in New York</i>

09:28.361 --> 09:31.239
<i>and I thought she could come out to</i>
<i>dinner with us tomorrow night</i>

09:31.322 --> 09:32.573
<i>and you could bring Neal.</i>

09:32.657 --> 09:34.075
<i>I think they'd really hit it off</i>

09:34.158 --> 09:35.576
<i>and you said he just broke up with somebody.</i>

09:35.660 --> 09:38.913
Neal's always just broken up with somebody.
He calls it going home in the morning.

09:38.996 --> 09:40.206
<i>It'll be a fun foursome.</i>

09:40.289 --> 09:42.541
<i>- Dinner and then straight to the hotel.</i>
- How many of us?

09:42.625 --> 09:45.336
<i>Jim, I'll have just finished covering</i>
<i>a $5,000-a-plate dinner.</i>

09:45.419 --> 09:46.963
<i>I'll be in cocktail attire.</i>

09:47.046 --> 09:48.422
Do it. Do it.

09:48.506 --> 09:50.466
Whatever she's asking to do, do it. Do it now.

09:50.549 --> 09:52.176
- You gonna be okay?
- Yeah.

09:52.260 --> 09:55.012
<i>- Hey, Gary.</i>
- Hey, Hallie.

09:55.096 --> 09:57.974
In terms of what you're gonna be wearing,
could you describe exactly what...

09:58.057 --> 10:00.017
<i>I'll see you guys tomorrow at 10:00?</i>

10:00.101 --> 10:01.519
- In the ballroom lobby.
<i>- I've got to go.</i>

10:01.602 --> 10:03.437
I'll talk to you later.

10:03.646 --> 10:04.814
(EXHALES)

10:04.897 --> 10:06.524
Neal.

10:06.607 --> 10:09.610
<i>Harry Truman dubbed the 80th</i>
<i>Congress the "Do-Nothing Congress."</i>

10:09.694 --> 10:13.614
<i>Its productivity, measured by this bar,</i>
<i>shows the number of laws they passed.</i>

10:13.698 --> 10:17.285
<i>The productivity of the 1 12th</i>
<i>Congress is measured by this bar.</i>

10:17.368 --> 10:20.621
The 112th Congress has not yet
passed one sixth of the laws

10:20.705 --> 10:21.998
of the Do-Nothing Congress.

10:22.081 --> 10:24.792
But let's look at the laws they have passed.

10:24.875 --> 10:28.462
<i>Congressman Peter Roskam</i>
<i>represents the 6th District of Illinois.</i>

10:28.546 --> 10:30.673
<i>Illinois has the fourth</i>
<i>highest unemployment rate</i>

10:30.756 --> 10:34.051
<i>in the country with 9.9%</i>
<i>of its workforce out of work.</i>

10:34.135 --> 10:38.180
<i>So Congressman Roskam introduced</i>
<i>House Resolution 21-39,</i>

10:38.264 --> 10:40.433
<i>which would require</i>
<i>the Secretary of the Treasury</i>

10:40.516 --> 10:44.937
<i>to mint coins in commemoration</i>
<i>of the centennial of the Lions Club.</i>

10:45.021 --> 10:46.856
Congressman Randy Forbes of Virginia

10:46.939 --> 10:50.735
sponsored a bill reaffirming
"In God We Trust" as our national motto,

10:50.818 --> 10:53.779
a motto already made official in 1956,

10:53.863 --> 10:57.658
2002, 2006 and now 2011.

10:57.742 --> 11:00.036
One in four American children
are living in poverty,

11:00.119 --> 11:01.829
but the motto should take care of that.

11:01.912 --> 11:04.457
<i>We're fighting a war, a stagnant economy,</i>

11:04.540 --> 11:07.001
a failing education system
and climate change.

11:07.084 --> 11:11.547
The 112th Congress
has renamed 40 post offices.

11:11.630 --> 11:13.924
Richard Shelby, the ranking Republican

11:14.008 --> 11:15.509
<i>on the Senate Banking Committee,</i>

11:15.593 --> 11:18.095
<i>blocked the appointment</i>
<i>of MIT economist Peter Diamond</i>

11:18.220 --> 11:20.598
<i>to a vacant seat on the Federal Reserve Board.</i>

11:20.681 --> 11:24.101
<i>Said Shelby, "I do not believe</i>
<i>the current environment of uncertainty</i>

11:24.185 --> 11:26.437
<i>"would benefit from</i>
<i>monetary policy decisions</i>

11:26.520 --> 11:28.856
<i>"made by board members</i>
<i>who are learning on the job."</i>

11:28.939 --> 11:31.484
<i>While Senator Shelby held up</i>
<i>Peter Diamond's nomination</i>

11:31.567 --> 11:34.236
<i>on the grounds that Diamond</i>
<i>was insufficiently qualified</i>

11:34.320 --> 11:36.280
<i>to counsel the Federal Reserve Board,</i>

11:36.364 --> 11:38.741
<i>Peter Diamond won</i>
<i>the Nobel Prize for economics.</i>

11:38.824 --> 11:39.950
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

11:40.242 --> 11:41.994
- You busy?
- No.

11:42.078 --> 11:45.039
Hey, this may sound nuts,
but I'm looking at the movie <i>John Carter</i>

11:45.122 --> 11:46.749
as a possible subject
for my <i>News Night</i> segment.

11:46.832 --> 11:47.917
What about it?

11:48.000 --> 11:50.252
Well, it's about a Civil War Confederate officer

11:50.336 --> 11:52.713
who's transported to Mars,
which is a lush planet

11:52.797 --> 11:54.548
inhabited by 12-foot-tall barbarians.

11:54.632 --> 11:56.384
Because of his different bone density

11:56.467 --> 11:57.885
and the planet's low gravity,
John Carter can jump...

11:57.968 --> 12:00.638
I said, "What about it?" not,
"What's it about?" Also, you know, spoilers.

12:00.721 --> 12:03.224
Okay, well, it's projected to
lose about 200 million for Disney.

12:03.307 --> 12:04.642
You want to do the economics of Hollywood?

12:04.725 --> 12:07.061
Say what you want,
but they're one of the few American industries

12:07.144 --> 12:08.646
still making a product people want to buy.

12:08.729 --> 12:10.356
Doesn't sound like
they want to buy <i>John Carter.</i>

12:10.439 --> 12:12.316
Well, that's my point.
Nobody's gonna ask for a bailout

12:12.400 --> 12:14.276
and Disney stock is relatively safe.

12:14.360 --> 12:17.321
Entertainment is one of our
highest revenue-generating exports

12:17.405 --> 12:19.657
and they employ members
of 17 different unions,

12:19.740 --> 12:22.410
all of which have excellent
minimum basic contracts.

12:22.493 --> 12:25.037
They may take it in the teeth on <i>John Carter,</i>
but nobody's gonna get hurt.

12:25.121 --> 12:26.622
It's still early. It's just a first idea.

12:26.705 --> 12:28.666
- Yeah, no, it sounds good.
- What are you doing?

12:28.749 --> 12:30.584
Looking at last night's show.

12:30.668 --> 12:32.503
- They did a focus group?
- No.

12:32.586 --> 12:34.588
There are dial lines
on the bottom of the screen.

12:34.672 --> 12:37.299
Yeah, those are just... That's...

12:37.383 --> 12:39.051
What's going on?

12:39.135 --> 12:40.845
I did a focus group. I did it myself.

12:40.928 --> 12:42.847
I called our company and did it on my own.

12:42.930 --> 12:45.599
They did the dials
and a moderator got comments after.

12:45.683 --> 12:47.518
- Why?
- Why?

12:47.601 --> 12:49.103
- Yeah.
- To check in.

12:49.186 --> 12:50.604
Why does a politician take polls?

12:50.688 --> 12:52.606
To find out what people
want him to say the next day.

12:52.690 --> 12:53.941
Are you comfortable with that analogy?

12:54.024 --> 12:56.527
Charlie doesn't allow me
to be tested anymore.

12:56.610 --> 12:58.487
So I did it myself.

12:59.905 --> 13:01.782
We have kind of
a big brother-little sister relationship.

13:01.866 --> 13:03.451
- Which one are you?
- And the little sister always ends up

13:03.534 --> 13:05.619
chewing out the big brother
and he says, "Thanks, sis."

13:05.786 --> 13:07.621
This is on Nickelodeon?

13:07.705 --> 13:10.458
- Never mind.
- Are you preparing for a chewing out?

13:12.251 --> 13:13.878
Nah.

13:13.961 --> 13:15.963
You forgot to ask me
how the test scores were.

13:16.046 --> 13:17.298
I didn't forget.

13:19.383 --> 13:21.469
CHARLIE: 427. 427.

13:21.552 --> 13:23.471
Are the odd numbers
on the right side or the left side?

13:23.554 --> 13:25.014
I can't see any numbers yet.

13:25.097 --> 13:27.433
All right, you look on the right side,
I'll look on the left side.

13:27.516 --> 13:30.311
I'm already on the left side.
Why don't you look on the right side?

13:30.394 --> 13:32.146
I'll look on the right side.

13:32.229 --> 13:33.898
(BRAKES SCREECH)

13:35.441 --> 13:36.567
(CHARLIE SIGHS)

13:42.198 --> 13:44.742
Hey, found it.

13:45.993 --> 13:47.912
- Is it this house or that house?
- I don't know.

13:47.995 --> 13:51.290
Let's just clean this up
and ring both doorbells.

13:51.373 --> 13:54.001
What are you doing in my garbage cans?

13:54.084 --> 13:57.213
- General Stomtonovich?
- Yeah.

13:57.296 --> 13:59.215
I'm sorry we're a little late.

13:59.298 --> 14:00.883
What are you doing in my garbage cans?

14:00.966 --> 14:02.968
We ran over them with our rental car.

14:03.052 --> 14:04.929
We're just gonna get this cleaned up.

14:05.012 --> 14:06.972
Were you texting?

14:07.056 --> 14:09.725
No, sir. It was regular negligence.

14:10.226 --> 14:12.436
Well, hurry up and tell me what you want.

14:15.648 --> 14:17.816
I'm sorry, sir. You're General Stom...

14:17.900 --> 14:19.318
I know who I am.

14:19.401 --> 14:22.071
I'm asking who you are
and how I can help you.

14:22.154 --> 14:25.115
- I'm Charlie Skinner.
- MacKenzie McHale.

14:25.491 --> 14:26.617
Hmm.

14:26.700 --> 14:28.744
How about if I write you a check for $100

14:28.827 --> 14:31.539
and you send the magazine
subscriptions to whoever you want?

14:34.041 --> 14:36.585
Sir, we spoke to you on the phone yesterday.

14:36.669 --> 14:38.504
We made an appointment
to see you here at your house.

14:40.297 --> 14:42.967
Yeah, right. That's too bad.

14:43.676 --> 14:45.970
I like arguing with Jehovah's Witnesses.

14:46.053 --> 14:47.096
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

14:47.179 --> 14:49.056
You want to know
how chemical weapons are stored?

14:49.139 --> 14:50.307
MACKENZIE: Yes, sir.

14:50.391 --> 14:51.475
All right.

14:52.226 --> 14:54.895
What is the Marine
Combat Munitions Element?

14:54.979 --> 14:57.565
We oversee all or almost all

14:57.648 --> 15:00.693
of the munitions
supplies for the entirety of the Marine Corps.

15:00.776 --> 15:03.571
- Bullets, bombs...
- And that includes chemical...

15:03.654 --> 15:05.030
Foul him. Foul him now!

15:05.114 --> 15:06.490
ANNOUNCER ON TV: <i>And he buries a three.</i>

15:06.615 --> 15:07.825
(GROANS)

15:09.159 --> 15:10.828
March Madness. (CHUCKLES)

15:11.287 --> 15:12.830
Best sporting event on Earth.

15:12.913 --> 15:14.999
Better than the Super Bowl, World Series...

15:15.082 --> 15:17.209
- Better than the World Cup?
- World Cup?

15:17.293 --> 15:19.587
- What are you, from Brazil?
- Brooklyn.

15:19.670 --> 15:21.338
(LAUGHS)

15:21.880 --> 15:27.595
2003, Gaddafi announced Libya
would voluntarily eliminate all materials,

15:27.678 --> 15:31.849
equipment and programs,
but they've still got 'em.

15:31.974 --> 15:33.475
- MACKENZIE: How about us?
- The US?

15:33.559 --> 15:35.436
- Yeah.
- Do we still have chemical weapons?

15:35.519 --> 15:36.604
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

15:36.687 --> 15:38.522
- We do?
- Yeah.

15:38.856 --> 15:41.567
Do you believe chemical weapons
are a legitimate weapon of war?

15:41.692 --> 15:44.111
I believe chemical weapons,
like any other weapons,

15:44.194 --> 15:46.280
are tools to be used to kill the enemy.

15:46.363 --> 15:48.741
Which tool you use
depends on battlefield circumstance.

15:48.824 --> 15:50.701
- And collateral damage?
- It doesn't make much difference

15:50.784 --> 15:53.912
to the collateral damage
whether it's damage by gas

15:53.996 --> 15:55.414
or a Hellfire missile, does it?

15:55.497 --> 15:57.708
So you think chemical weapons
should be part of our arsenal?

15:57.791 --> 15:59.209
Part of ours, not Libya's.

15:59.293 --> 16:01.795
Do you think
we should be able to use chemical weapons?

16:04.173 --> 16:06.383
Missed free throws is what kills you.

16:09.678 --> 16:10.721
MACKENZIE: General?

16:10.804 --> 16:12.556
I don't think I want to
talk about chemical weapons.

16:12.640 --> 16:13.932
- We think you do.
- Yeah?

16:14.016 --> 16:16.185
During a speech
at the War College two years ago,

16:16.268 --> 16:19.229
you were openly critical
of the destruction of our stockpiles.

16:19.313 --> 16:21.857
You've commissioned
two studies citing the potential need

16:21.940 --> 16:23.859
for chemical weapons in combat situations

16:23.942 --> 16:27.279
and your book was so heavily redacted
that all that was left were pronouns.

16:27.363 --> 16:29.365
Why are you two big shots
in Silver Spring, Maryland,

16:29.448 --> 16:32.951
running into my garbage cans
and asking me about sarin?

16:36.538 --> 16:38.957
General, we never mentioned sarin.

16:39.667 --> 16:41.669
We know about Genoa.

16:44.838 --> 16:46.256
(SIGHS)

16:49.760 --> 16:52.971
You can't touch a shooter
while he's in the process of shooting the ball.

16:53.055 --> 16:54.473
It's against the rules.

16:54.556 --> 16:56.934
Shooter goes to the foul line,
takes two free throws.

16:57.017 --> 17:00.354
But what happens
if the shooter brandishes a knife?

17:00.562 --> 17:04.525
He's dribbling the ball
and he suddenly takes out a switchblade.

17:04.608 --> 17:06.527
You're allowed to grab his arm now

17:06.610 --> 17:09.988
because we're not playing
basketball anymore.

17:12.074 --> 17:15.452
This is a helo manifest.
Can you confirm it's authentic?

17:15.703 --> 17:17.329
It's an authentic helo manifest.

17:17.413 --> 17:19.081
Can you confirm that Genoa happened?

17:19.164 --> 17:22.167
Why would I confirm, even off the record,
the existence of a classified mission?

17:22.251 --> 17:24.378
Because you believe
very strongly that if the shooter

17:24.461 --> 17:28.340
takes a knife out,
it shouldn't be illegal to grab his arm.

17:36.432 --> 17:37.641
(SIGHS)

17:38.809 --> 17:41.186
Here are my conditions.
You black out my face.

17:41.270 --> 17:42.855
- Sure.
- Alter my voice.

17:42.938 --> 17:44.732
- Mmm-hmm.
- That's it.

17:44.815 --> 17:46.650
We do it right here noon tomorrow.

17:46.734 --> 17:47.901
I want to be able to watch the games.

17:47.985 --> 17:50.279
- Not during the interview.
- I'm not turning that TV off.

17:50.362 --> 17:53.490
I don't know how many years
I have left after this thing goes on the air.

17:54.742 --> 17:57.077
The producer's name is Jerry Dantana.

17:57.161 --> 18:00.289
He's from the DC bureau
and it's been his story from the beginning.

18:01.081 --> 18:03.208
We have to head back to New York, General.

18:03.292 --> 18:04.877
It was nice meeting you.

18:04.960 --> 18:07.504
We won't have any more communication
after this unless it's necessary.

18:07.588 --> 18:09.548
How did he find it... Dantana?

18:09.631 --> 18:11.592
How did he find the story?

18:11.675 --> 18:13.469
Just a lucky tip.

18:13.552 --> 18:15.846
<i>And then very late in my political career,</i>

18:15.929 --> 18:18.849
<i>I had the opportunity</i>
<i>to read the speech and I almost threw up.</i>

18:19.516 --> 18:22.102
The speech that almost made
Senator Santorum vomit

18:22.186 --> 18:25.814
was given by John F. Kennedy
in Houston, Texas, in 1960.

18:25.898 --> 18:28.442
The presidential candidate
was answering concerns

18:28.525 --> 18:31.361
that his Catholicism
would be his compass in the Oval Office.

18:31.445 --> 18:33.947
And the Houston speech
made a forceful argument

18:34.031 --> 18:37.785
for a firewall between
religion, any religion, and government.

18:37.868 --> 18:40.621
With us by satellite
from Boulder, Colorado, is Randall Dell,

18:40.704 --> 18:43.957
President of the League of Catholic
Voters and a Santorum supporter.

18:44.041 --> 18:46.210
- Mr. Dell, welcome.
<i>- Good to be here.</i>

18:46.293 --> 18:48.504
<i>The common wisdom</i>
<i>is that political candidates</i>

18:48.587 --> 18:50.380
<i>shouldn't be asked</i>
<i>about their religious beliefs.</i>

18:50.464 --> 18:51.465
DELL: <i>I agree with that.</i>

18:51.548 --> 18:54.551
<i>But what if a candidate makes their religious</i>
<i>beliefs part of their candidacy?</i>

18:54.635 --> 18:56.303
DELL: <i>Is there a candidate who's doing that?</i>

18:56.386 --> 18:58.555
- The candidate you support is doing that.
<i>- That's not true, sir.</i>

18:58.639 --> 19:02.184
<i>Is Rick Santorum devout? Yes.</i>
<i>Does his faith guide his actions? Yes.</i>

19:02.267 --> 19:04.728
Does he say so every day
in campaign speeches? He does.

19:04.812 --> 19:06.230
Let's put this quote up on the screen.

19:06.313 --> 19:07.397
- G17-a.
- JOEY: Got it.

19:07.481 --> 19:09.691
WILL: <i>Rick Santorum speaking</i>
<i>at a Tea Party event in Columbus.</i>

19:09.775 --> 19:13.153
<i>He said this in regard</i>
<i>to President Obama's climate change agenda.</i>

19:13.237 --> 19:16.073
<i>"It's not about your quality of life.</i>
<i>It's not about your jobs.</i>

19:16.156 --> 19:19.368
<i>"It's about some phony ideal.</i>
<i>Some phony theology.</i>

19:19.451 --> 19:22.996
"Oh, not a theology based on the Bible.
A different theology."

19:23.080 --> 19:25.249
Mr. Dell, one of Rick Santorum's problems

19:25.332 --> 19:27.501
with the president's plan
to combat climate change

19:27.584 --> 19:29.419
is that its roots can't be found in the Bible.

19:29.503 --> 19:32.047
<i>We have a lot of reasons to be</i>
<i>concerned with Obama's plans,</i>

19:32.130 --> 19:34.299
<i>but you're plainly distorting</i>
<i>Rick Santorum's words.</i>

19:34.383 --> 19:36.218
WILL: I don't think I am,
but let's go to this instead.

19:36.301 --> 19:37.469
- HERB: 17B.
- Up.

19:37.553 --> 19:38.804
- Thirty seconds.
- Let it go long.

19:38.887 --> 19:42.182
WILL:...<i>at the Press and People of Faith</i>
<i>in Politics forum in 2008.</i>

19:42.266 --> 19:44.935
<i>"I think there are</i>
<i>a lot of problems with the theory of evolution</i>

19:45.018 --> 19:46.770
<i>"and I do believe it is used to promote</i>

19:46.854 --> 19:49.398
<i>"a world view</i>
<i>that is anti-theist, that is atheist.</i>

19:49.481 --> 19:52.609
"You should have academic freedom
in the classroom when teaching about life."

19:52.693 --> 19:55.070
- DELL: <i>That was 2008. Mr. Santorum...</i>
- Ready 18.

19:55.153 --> 19:56.613
<i>...made those remarks</i>
<i>when he didn't hold office.</i>

19:56.697 --> 19:58.365
<i>- He was speaking as a private citizen.</i>
- Ready.

19:58.448 --> 20:00.450
- HERB: Go.
- He was speaking in defense of an amendment

20:00.534 --> 20:03.078
he offered in 2001 when he was a US Senator,

20:03.161 --> 20:06.456
making it a federal law that,
"Where topics are taught

20:06.540 --> 20:09.459
<i>"that may generate controversy,</i>
<i>such as biological evolution,</i>

20:09.543 --> 20:11.461
<i>"the curriculum should help</i>
<i>students to understand</i>

20:11.545 --> 20:14.214
<i>"the full range of scientific views that exist."</i>

20:14.298 --> 20:16.049
<i>By full range of scientific views,</i>

20:16.133 --> 20:18.176
- he's including Genesis, right?
<i>- That's right.</i>

20:18.260 --> 20:20.178
It seems like far from objecting that religion

20:20.262 --> 20:22.764
be brought up in political campaigns,
he's insisting on it.

20:22.848 --> 20:25.350
<i>And here's Rick Santorum's opponent,</i>
<i>Mitt Romney,</i>

20:25.434 --> 20:27.227
<i>- asking us not to ask about his religion.</i>
- 22.

20:27.311 --> 20:29.897
<i>That idea that we should choose people</i>

20:29.980 --> 20:32.733
<i>based upon their religion for public office</i>

20:32.816 --> 20:35.027
<i>is what I find to be most troubling,</i>

20:35.110 --> 20:37.571
<i>because the founders of this country</i>
<i>went to great length</i>

20:37.654 --> 20:40.616
<i>to make sure,</i>
<i>and even put it in the Constitution,</i>

20:40.699 --> 20:43.076
<i>that we would not choose</i>
<i>people who represent us</i>

20:43.160 --> 20:44.620
<i>in government based upon their religion.</i>

20:44.703 --> 20:47.164
And now here he is invoking his religion.

20:47.247 --> 20:49.416
<i>The Declaration of Independence</i>
<i>established our rights</i>

20:49.499 --> 20:53.462
<i>by saying that they were created</i>
<i>not by government, but by the Creator.</i>

20:53.545 --> 20:56.632
<i>We are endowed</i>
<i>by our Creator with certain unalienable rights.</i>

20:56.715 --> 20:58.926
<i>I will fight to preserve America's tradition</i>
<i>as a religious nation.</i>

20:59.009 --> 21:00.135
(APPLAUSE ON TAPE)

21:00.218 --> 21:02.471
So, can we really not ask
these candidates questions

21:02.554 --> 21:04.431
about what they believe
with regard to religion?

21:04.514 --> 21:05.599
<i>Well, like what?</i>

21:05.682 --> 21:09.102
Like is it important that you and I
have the same definition of "creator"?

21:09.186 --> 21:10.562
<i>They plainly meant God.</i>

21:10.646 --> 21:12.189
<i>That's not plain to everybody.</i>

21:12.814 --> 21:16.068
Like right there.
Just a smile would have made it folksier.

21:16.151 --> 21:18.570
Also, honey,
you've got to stay away from religion.

21:18.654 --> 21:19.988
You know you're just asking for it.

21:20.072 --> 21:21.490
What else am I supposed to talk about

21:21.573 --> 21:23.033
with the President
of the League of Catholic Voters?

21:23.116 --> 21:25.786
You don't have him on as a guest.
That's another thing.

21:25.869 --> 21:28.288
You want guests that don't
make you look so combative.

21:28.372 --> 21:30.248
That's why your likability numbers are down.

21:30.374 --> 21:32.125
- I don't know. I think I'm likable.
- I think you're lovable.

21:32.209 --> 21:35.253
- Thank you.
- But your numbers are problematic.

21:36.546 --> 21:40.968
Listen to me, I'd like dinner to last
10 to 15 minutes.

21:41.051 --> 21:42.469
You don't like to linger.

21:42.552 --> 21:44.471
I'm doing my lingering
somewhere else tonight,

21:44.554 --> 21:46.974
so we're not ordering
anything that takes a long time to prepare.

21:47.057 --> 21:49.643
We're not ordering anything well-done.
We're not ordering anything cooked.

21:49.726 --> 21:51.061
It's okay with me if we don't order anything.

21:51.144 --> 21:52.604
It's not going to be okay with the restaurant.

21:52.688 --> 21:53.814
Screw the restaurant, Neal.

21:53.897 --> 21:56.400
The restaurant hasn't
not seen his girlfriend in a month.

21:56.483 --> 22:00.070
The restaurant's girlfriend
isn't wearing cocktail attire.

22:00.153 --> 22:02.531
- You gonna be okay?
- Yeah, I'm fine.

22:02.614 --> 22:05.492
Six minutes and 20 seconds.

22:05.659 --> 22:07.077
God, it's you.

22:07.160 --> 22:09.037
That's how long you spent
tonight on Etch-a-Sketch.

22:09.663 --> 22:12.499
- Six minutes and 20 seconds.
- Hey, Taylor.

22:12.582 --> 22:14.418
- Hi, Jim.
- You look very nice.

22:14.501 --> 22:16.753
- Thank you.
- This is Neal Sampat. We work together.

22:16.837 --> 22:19.131
Neal, this is Taylor Warren,
a Romney campaign spokesman.

22:19.214 --> 22:21.508
- Woman... Spokesperson.
- Nice to meet you.

22:21.591 --> 22:23.301
- You work for ACN?
- Yes.

22:23.427 --> 22:26.179
I loathe you in ways that are unquantifiable.

22:26.680 --> 22:27.848
Cool.

22:27.931 --> 22:30.434
- You must be excited to see Hallie.
- I am.

22:30.517 --> 22:33.562
I mentioned to Hallie that I didn't have
anything to do in the city tonight.

22:33.645 --> 22:34.688
No.

22:34.771 --> 22:36.440
And she said
that I should join you guys for dinner.

22:37.774 --> 22:40.861
(LAUGHS) You should see
the look on your face.

22:40.944 --> 22:43.196
Don't worry, I know you had
a special night planned,

22:43.280 --> 22:45.198
so of course I'm coming along.
You know why?

22:45.282 --> 22:46.575
Because we spent
six minutes and 20 seconds...

22:46.658 --> 22:47.784
On Etch-a-Sketch, yeah.

22:47.868 --> 22:50.287
- It was a story and you know it.
- No, it was a gaffe and you know it.

22:50.370 --> 22:53.165
He came out and said, "Don't worry about
anything I've said during the primary.

22:53.248 --> 22:54.666
"I can be whatever you want me to be."

22:54.750 --> 22:56.209
He didn't say it. Fehrnstrom did.

22:56.293 --> 22:57.794
And how do you expect us to juggle

22:57.878 --> 23:00.589
very diverse coalitions
inside the Republican party?

23:00.672 --> 23:03.341
- Really glad I came tonight.
- There's no way you're coming to dinner.

23:03.425 --> 23:04.718
Jim.

23:08.680 --> 23:10.515
- I've missed you.
- You look amazing.

23:10.599 --> 23:12.017
- Plus?
- I've missed you, too.

23:12.100 --> 23:13.685
There it is. This is Aubrey.

23:13.769 --> 23:15.479
Hey, it's nice to meet you. Neal.

23:15.562 --> 23:18.356
Okay, full disclosure,
the press wasn't allowed any food,

23:18.440 --> 23:20.275
but we stole a couple bottles of Chardonnay

23:20.358 --> 23:22.402
- and I am wicked hammered.
- Okay.

23:22.486 --> 23:25.697
- Neal, this is Aubrey.
- Hey.

23:25.781 --> 23:26.823
- Nice to meet you.
- Full disclosure...

23:26.907 --> 23:28.075
The press wasn't allowed any food,

23:28.158 --> 23:29.618
but we stole a couple bottles of Chardonnay...

23:29.701 --> 23:31.703
- Wicked hammered.
- You said that already.

23:31.787 --> 23:33.246
We're gonna get some food in your stomach.

23:33.330 --> 23:35.248
Maybe that's not necessary.

23:36.333 --> 23:39.336
So, listen, Taylor's kind of sad tonight.

23:39.419 --> 23:41.296
I don't know why,
so I asked her to come to dinner.

23:41.379 --> 23:43.090
She's not sad. She's mad 'cause we did

23:43.173 --> 23:45.092
six minutes and 20 seconds on Etch-a-Sketch.

23:45.175 --> 23:48.053
And now I have to have a dinner with her
that could last up to a half hour.

23:48.136 --> 23:49.846
You're afraid of Taylor.

23:49.930 --> 23:52.099
Being afraid of Taylor
is just good common sense.

23:52.182 --> 23:53.934
- Anybody hungry?
- I can boot and rally.

23:54.017 --> 23:55.560
Let's do it.

23:55.644 --> 23:57.729
- You here alone?
- Yeah. You?

23:57.813 --> 23:59.022
I am.

23:59.523 --> 24:02.651
This is what I do now.
I drink alone at bars late at night.

24:02.734 --> 24:05.278
See, men can do that with no stigma attached.

24:05.362 --> 24:06.446
- Women...
- Women can vote

24:06.530 --> 24:08.281
and your vote counts the same as my vote.

24:08.365 --> 24:11.326
I'm really supposed to worry about a stigma?

24:11.827 --> 24:12.953
Oh, Don.

24:13.036 --> 24:14.454
Don, Don.

24:15.330 --> 24:16.623
Don.

24:17.040 --> 24:18.375
Are you happy with that name?

24:19.918 --> 24:22.170
Pretty happy. Never really thought about it.

24:22.254 --> 24:23.547
How'd it go in Maryland?

24:23.672 --> 24:25.173
He confirmed.

24:27.884 --> 24:29.052
Will he do it on camera?

24:29.719 --> 24:30.971
- Find out tomorrow.
- Hey, Mac.

24:31.054 --> 24:33.515
- What do you say, Chelsea?
- You here alone?

24:33.598 --> 24:35.559
- Don't stigmatize her.
- Where's the gang?

24:35.642 --> 24:37.269
Jim and Neal are on a double date,

24:37.352 --> 24:39.312
Sloan is out with a New York Giant,

24:39.396 --> 24:43.233
and Will's having
a quiet night at home with Mrs. Macbeth.

24:43.650 --> 24:45.110
HALLIE: He took some questions
from the audience

24:45.193 --> 24:46.987
and somebody asked him
if he thought the court

24:47.070 --> 24:48.488
was going to overturn the ACA.

24:48.572 --> 24:50.490
And I thought he was
gonna duck the question,

24:50.574 --> 24:52.159
but he answered for about two minutes.

24:52.242 --> 24:54.119
- What did he say?
- I swear to God, I don't know.

24:54.202 --> 24:55.787
Can I ask something?

24:55.871 --> 24:58.165
What's the fucking obsession
with Ann Romney's horse?

24:58.248 --> 25:00.667
- Reagan had a horse.
- His horse didn't dance.

25:00.750 --> 25:03.086
So fucking what, James? It's a clever horse.

25:03.170 --> 25:04.588
It's an Olympian. It's a horse.

25:04.671 --> 25:06.214
And what in this is bad?

25:06.298 --> 25:08.341
And how do you know
that Reagan's horse didn't dance?

25:08.425 --> 25:09.885
It's a reasonable question, James.

25:09.968 --> 25:11.678
How did you get into campaign reporting?

25:11.761 --> 25:14.097
I told my bosses that nobody
was covering Ron Paul

25:14.181 --> 25:15.682
and they were like, "Go do it yourself."

25:15.765 --> 25:17.559
And I was like, "Really?"
And they were like, "Really."

25:17.642 --> 25:19.352
So Ron Paul, 2012!

25:19.436 --> 25:20.729
- Is this your...
- (WHOOPING)

25:20.812 --> 25:23.023
- Okay.
- Seriously?

25:23.106 --> 25:24.900
Yeah, she's into it.

25:28.778 --> 25:30.488
- Hey.
- Hi.

25:30.572 --> 25:32.282
- You're back again.
- Yeah.

25:32.365 --> 25:34.743
- It was Stoli and tonic?
- Yeah.

25:34.951 --> 25:36.745
- I'm Devon.
- Maggie.

25:39.998 --> 25:41.708
NINA: <i>I admire MacKenzie.</i>

25:41.791 --> 25:43.710
- And Charlie.
- So do I.

25:43.793 --> 25:45.462
I know you do.

25:45.545 --> 25:48.215
But I wonder
if it's blinding you to certain things.

25:48.298 --> 25:49.591
Like what?

25:50.300 --> 25:53.970
Well, honey, every night
you cross examine somebody.

25:54.054 --> 25:56.223
They're using your prosecutorial skills.

25:56.306 --> 25:59.559
Wait. First, they're not my puppet masters.
I'm the managing editor.

25:59.643 --> 26:01.353
But don't you always listen to MacKenzie?

26:01.436 --> 26:03.313
- Not always.
- What percent of the time?

26:03.396 --> 26:04.981
I don't know. But the idea is

26:05.065 --> 26:07.025
that we cross examine
people from time to time.

26:07.108 --> 26:09.569
- We?
- A lot of staff prep goes into those segments.

26:09.653 --> 26:11.321
But the staff's face isn't on camera.

26:11.404 --> 26:13.490
What are we talking about?

26:14.324 --> 26:16.243
Are you being sacrificed

26:16.326 --> 26:19.579
so that Mac and Charlie
can do the show they want to do?

26:19.663 --> 26:21.206
It's the show I want to do, too.

26:21.289 --> 26:22.832
- Is it?
- Yeah.

26:23.333 --> 26:25.460
Then that's that.
If it's the show you want to do,

26:25.543 --> 26:28.672
then who cares how many people like you?
I like you.

26:29.589 --> 26:33.260
It actually doesn't measure
how many people like you.

26:33.343 --> 26:34.844
It measures how much people like you.

26:34.928 --> 26:36.429
- How much?
- Yeah.

26:36.513 --> 26:39.599
- That's not something that can be measured.
- That's right.

26:39.683 --> 26:42.477
So this is really all there is to go on?

26:45.647 --> 26:48.191
Do you fully trust Jerry Dantana?

26:48.275 --> 26:50.944
- Why wouldn't I?
- No reason. I was just curious.

26:51.027 --> 26:53.613
- But there's a reason you're asking.
- There really isn't.

26:53.697 --> 26:55.949
- Can I tell you what it is?
- It was just curiosity.

26:56.032 --> 26:57.951
- It's 'cause he's not Jim.
- Please.

26:58.034 --> 27:00.704
Jerry has committed
the crime of not being Jim Harper.

27:00.787 --> 27:02.789
You know how long it took you to trust me?

27:02.872 --> 27:05.375
- How long?
- I'll let you know when it happens.

27:05.458 --> 27:07.585
I completely trust you.

27:09.004 --> 27:10.922
- Do you?
- With my life, Don.

27:11.006 --> 27:12.841
Thank you. That's nice to hear.

27:12.924 --> 27:15.468
You know, when I look at you...

27:15.552 --> 27:18.471
- Sloan's going out with a football player?
- Yeah.

27:18.555 --> 27:20.307
- Who?
- I don't remember his name.

27:20.390 --> 27:21.808
- You know what position he plays?
- No.

27:21.891 --> 27:23.310
- Offense or defense?
- I don't know.

27:23.393 --> 27:24.728
Why don't you just ask her out?

27:24.811 --> 27:26.354
After she's gone out
with a professional athlete

27:26.438 --> 27:29.399
who's 10 years younger than I am
with three percent body fat

27:29.482 --> 27:31.109
and ripped muscles
that have been conditioned

27:31.192 --> 27:33.570
over a lifetime of two-a-days sweating...

27:33.653 --> 27:35.405
How long have you been
thinking about this guy?

27:35.488 --> 27:36.906
How am I supposed to follow that?

27:37.032 --> 27:39.784
- And, you know...
- Get it done?

27:39.868 --> 27:41.953
I can get it done.

27:42.037 --> 27:43.371
I'm saying...

27:44.539 --> 27:46.916
get it done in a spectacular fashion.

27:47.000 --> 27:48.251
(BOTH LAUGHING)

27:49.044 --> 27:50.587
This is how most men think?

27:50.670 --> 27:54.007
This is how every single man thinks
except for the guy out with Sloan right now.

27:54.090 --> 27:56.968
And that's why you haven't asked her out?

27:57.052 --> 28:01.222
Sometimes she subs in for Elliot
and sometimes she does a segment with us,

28:01.306 --> 28:02.849
which means sometimes I'm her boss.

28:02.932 --> 28:05.685
That stopped absolutely no one here,
including you and Maggie.

28:05.769 --> 28:08.313
That worked out phenomenally well.

28:08.396 --> 28:10.106
Nothing that happened to her is your fault.

28:13.485 --> 28:15.278
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

28:15.362 --> 28:16.821
- It's really good.
- Me, too.

28:16.905 --> 28:18.114
(TAYLOR SHOUTING)

28:19.032 --> 28:20.700
That's the spicy Shanghai soup noodles,

28:20.784 --> 28:23.495
- chilled silken tofu garlic and herbs?
- WAITRESS: Yes, it is.

28:23.578 --> 28:25.330
- How'd you recognize that?
- It's kind of a hobby.

28:25.413 --> 28:27.374
And here's the charred
chili rubbed beef skewer.

28:27.457 --> 28:29.209
- With Thai basil dipping sauce.
- WAITRESS: That's right.

28:29.292 --> 28:30.543
- AUBREY: So, Jim.
- Yeah?

28:30.627 --> 28:32.045
- I have to tell you something.
- Okay.

28:32.128 --> 28:34.506
The <i>Sex and the City</i> story
is off-the-charts awesome.

28:34.589 --> 28:36.257
- TAYLOR: What's the <i>Sex and the City</i> story?
- Please, no.

28:36.341 --> 28:37.634
- AUBREY: You haven't heard this?
- I haven't.

28:37.717 --> 28:39.511
Is it an embarrassing story about Jim?

28:39.594 --> 28:41.596
- It's not embarrassing. It's sweet.
- TAYLOR: I'd like to hear it.

28:41.679 --> 28:43.181
I'd like to hear it as many times

28:43.264 --> 28:46.101
as ACN's run
the "I like to fire people" sound bite.

28:46.184 --> 28:48.561
- Everybody ran it, Taylor.
- And everybody, including you,

28:48.645 --> 28:50.563
knew what he meant when he said it.

28:50.647 --> 28:52.399
Let's play the game
where we identify the food.

28:52.482 --> 28:54.859
- What's this?
- You're pointing at rice.

28:54.943 --> 28:56.403
I believe that's correct.

28:56.486 --> 28:58.238
You know, I could tell the story...

28:58.321 --> 29:00.740
- Yep.
- ...or we can watch it on YouTube.

29:00.824 --> 29:02.325
(CHUCKLES) Oh, sweet.

29:02.450 --> 29:04.494
I'm starting to feel responsible for this.

29:05.995 --> 29:07.622
What about <i>ACN Morning?</i>

29:07.705 --> 29:10.166
- You think I should go on?
- I think you should start there.

29:10.792 --> 29:14.587
I think you need to warm yourself up
and a morning show is a great place to start.

29:14.671 --> 29:16.423
Just go on and do some jokes?

29:16.506 --> 29:19.509
Just be you. Nebraska farm boy.

29:19.676 --> 29:22.220
The guy who knows
how to build his own cabin.

29:22.303 --> 29:24.097
I don't know how to build my own cabin.

29:24.180 --> 29:27.100
Well, you seem like you do.
You need to seem like you do.

29:27.183 --> 29:29.269
Midwestern. You used to steal

29:29.352 --> 29:31.771
your mother's pies when
she put them out to cool.

29:31.855 --> 29:33.231
You're confusing me with a hobo.

29:33.314 --> 29:35.316
- You know what I'm saying.
- I think I do.

29:35.400 --> 29:37.277
- Then do it.
- Okay.

29:37.402 --> 29:39.279
- How about tomorrow morning?
- Well, it's after midnight.

29:39.362 --> 29:42.782
ACN is a network built around one person.

29:42.866 --> 29:46.244
You call the EP,
tell him you're coming on in the morning.

29:46.327 --> 29:49.289
You'll feel better
once you start to turn this around.

29:49.372 --> 29:52.250
- I will feel better.
- 75s become 85s fast,

29:52.333 --> 29:54.544
but they become 55s faster.

29:57.547 --> 29:58.965
All right.

30:01.968 --> 30:05.305
That gentleman over there
would like to buy this for you.

30:09.893 --> 30:13.980
This is nice of you, but I have to tell you
I'm just hanging out alone tonight.

30:14.063 --> 30:16.107
- MAN: That's okay.
- It's nothing personal.

30:16.191 --> 30:17.400
The drink's on me anyway.

30:17.484 --> 30:19.569
Very kind. Thank you.

30:20.445 --> 30:23.448
- I'm just thinking my thoughts.
- MAN: Understood.

30:27.410 --> 30:29.329
TAYLOR: <i>I have a number of questions.</i>

30:29.412 --> 30:33.124
I'll try to answer them with the same detail
and honesty you've always answered mine.

30:33.208 --> 30:35.835
What were you doing on
a <i>Sex and the City</i> tour bus to begin with?

30:35.919 --> 30:39.172
My girlfriend at the time liked the show
and I was showing an interest in her interests.

30:39.255 --> 30:42.008
And Maggie didn't know you were on the bus
when she shouted that she loved you?

30:42.091 --> 30:43.343
That's not what she shouted.

30:43.426 --> 30:44.844
- And she didn't know someone was filming it?
- No.

30:44.928 --> 30:46.846
- So it was kind of a gaffe?
- Lady, I...

30:46.930 --> 30:49.682
Life and death and you guys
can't get past "corporations are people."

30:49.766 --> 30:52.727
How fast are we supposed to get past
"Hispanics should self-deport"

30:52.810 --> 30:54.562
or "I'm not concerned with the very poor"?

30:54.646 --> 30:57.315
"There's a safety net there"
was the end of that sentence,

30:57.398 --> 30:59.609
and plainly his concern
is with the middle class.

30:59.692 --> 31:01.236
The middle class are the very poor.

31:01.319 --> 31:04.364
The better point is
we don't need clean air and water regulations.

31:04.447 --> 31:07.283
We don't need FEMA.
We don't need antitrust laws.

31:07.367 --> 31:11.538
We don't need the IRS or the Department of
Education or the Federal Reserve.

31:11.621 --> 31:13.665
We need freedom.

31:15.250 --> 31:16.709
What the fuck did you just say?

31:16.793 --> 31:18.711
AUBREY: If you listen to Ron Paul...

31:18.795 --> 31:21.047
I have. He's a batty old crank

31:21.130 --> 31:24.175
who wrote instruction manuals on how to
get away with shooting the black kid

31:24.259 --> 31:26.219
who's stealing your car. He's not Betty White.

31:26.302 --> 31:27.887
- He didn't write those letters.
- Yes, he did.

31:27.971 --> 31:30.056
And then he signed them
and then he charged money for them.

31:30.139 --> 31:32.600
So I don't give a shit
if he wants to legalize weed.

31:32.684 --> 31:34.644
I can already dial the phone
and have an ounce

31:34.727 --> 31:36.229
delivered to this table
before the check comes.

31:36.312 --> 31:38.273
- Then for God's sake, do it.
- The check will never come.

31:38.356 --> 31:40.108
They won't let Romney
get his message out, either.

31:40.191 --> 31:42.235
JIM: Someone should tell him
if he wants to get his message out,

31:42.318 --> 31:44.862
he should consider appearing on a network

31:44.946 --> 31:47.657
where the entire audience
isn't already voting for him

31:47.740 --> 31:49.742
and that if he's gonna be
the businessman president,

31:49.826 --> 31:53.079
he should run on his business record
instead of pretending he's never heard of it

31:53.162 --> 31:56.124
and that if faith is important to
his good works and personal narrative,

31:56.207 --> 31:57.750
he shouldn't be afraid it'll creep us out.

31:57.834 --> 31:59.252
- It's been suggested.
- And?

31:59.335 --> 32:00.753
I was fired.

32:03.214 --> 32:05.925
- I was fired tonight.
- You were fired?

32:06.009 --> 32:07.468
- Yeah.
- For suggesting...

32:07.552 --> 32:10.138
No, I suggested other things, too.

32:12.974 --> 32:14.392
I'm sorry.

32:14.976 --> 32:16.978
You were a good spokesperson for him.

32:19.022 --> 32:21.274
You should go work for Ron Paul.

32:22.692 --> 32:24.110
HALLIE: We need to rebound from dinner.

32:24.193 --> 32:25.612
- Yeah.
- Bounce back.

32:25.695 --> 32:27.655
- I've already bounced.
- It's just us now.

32:27.739 --> 32:29.866
With a little over six hours.

32:31.909 --> 32:33.411
This is...

32:40.043 --> 32:41.252
Maggie?

32:41.919 --> 32:43.880
- Hi.
- What are you doing here?

32:43.963 --> 32:46.924
I'm just having a drink
with a friend of mine from college.

32:47.008 --> 32:48.885
What are you doing here?

32:50.094 --> 32:52.680
Jim's fixing my computer. I'm staying here.

32:52.764 --> 32:56.059
This is Hallie Shea.
Hallie, this is Maggie Jordan.

32:56.142 --> 32:58.728
- Hi. You, too.
- It's nice to meet you.

32:59.228 --> 33:00.772
Well, we should...

33:00.855 --> 33:04.275
- I have to be on the press plane pretty early.
- Yeah.

33:05.401 --> 33:07.236
- Good meeting you.
- You, too.

33:07.320 --> 33:08.863
See you later.

33:12.992 --> 33:15.995
- That was nice of you.
- I doubt it mattered.

33:20.750 --> 33:22.627
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

33:23.586 --> 33:24.754
Wow.

33:25.421 --> 33:28.174
Is there something wrong with the room?

33:36.891 --> 33:39.894
I am not unskilled in the ways of courtship.

33:39.977 --> 33:43.356
I know, babe, but still, just saying that...

33:44.399 --> 33:46.025
(CELL PHONE CHIMING)

33:49.070 --> 33:51.072
I am pouring you some champagne

33:51.155 --> 33:53.366
and then taking a hot shower.

33:53.449 --> 33:56.452
Can I offer you a Toblerone from the minibar?

33:57.787 --> 33:59.997
- Honey.
- What is it?

34:00.081 --> 34:04.001
They just added on an event
at a base in Colorado for the morning.

34:04.085 --> 34:05.461
For tomorrow morning?

34:05.545 --> 34:07.797
I have to be on a plane in 90 minutes.

34:08.506 --> 34:09.799
MACKENZIE: <i>Are you religious?</i>

34:10.758 --> 34:13.469
- In my way.
- Me, too.

34:14.053 --> 34:16.139
I think the way
you know you've broken one of God's rules

34:16.222 --> 34:19.183
is if you can't put it back together again.

34:19.767 --> 34:22.103
You kidnap an entire people,

34:22.186 --> 34:24.605
make them slaves, it's 300 years later

34:24.689 --> 34:26.232
and we can't put it back together again.

34:26.315 --> 34:27.942
You and Will?

34:28.025 --> 34:29.736
Doesn't really seem like the same scale.

34:29.819 --> 34:32.155
- As slavery?
- Yeah.

34:32.238 --> 34:33.573
- (BOTH LAUGHING)
- No.

34:34.532 --> 34:36.117
But here we are.

34:36.784 --> 34:39.704
- You should go out.
- I do.

34:39.787 --> 34:40.913
You'll meet someone.

34:46.294 --> 34:47.712
You're sure you trust Jerry?

34:47.795 --> 34:49.464
I have no reason not to.

34:51.382 --> 34:56.220
Mac, if Charlie green lights it
and Will and the lawyers,

34:59.348 --> 35:00.933
you still have to consider not running it.

35:01.017 --> 35:02.894
- I know.
- The size of this...

35:02.977 --> 35:04.854
- I've thought about the risk.
- Embassies will be attacked.

35:04.937 --> 35:06.397
- POWs will...
- There'll be protests.

35:06.481 --> 35:08.065
Protests in some countries
look a lot like riots.

35:08.149 --> 35:09.442
Muslims will go crazy.

35:09.525 --> 35:11.569
I was at <i>Newsweek</i> in 2005.

35:15.448 --> 35:17.492
For the guy who flushed
a Koran down the toilet?

35:17.575 --> 35:19.285
Yeah. We report the story

35:19.368 --> 35:21.245
and two months later,
the London subway blows up.

35:21.329 --> 35:23.539
- It's not clear the two were connected.
- The bomber's cousin said...

35:23.623 --> 35:26.542
- Somebody was gonna report it.
- Ah, maybe not.

35:29.128 --> 35:30.588
Maybe not.

35:30.922 --> 35:34.967
Anyway, I hope you're considering
cause and effect,

35:35.051 --> 35:36.677
'cause if we broke one of God's rules,

35:36.761 --> 35:39.013
it might be best just to shut up about it.

35:39.096 --> 35:40.431
(CHUCKLES)

35:50.441 --> 35:52.276
Where's your friend?

35:52.360 --> 35:55.196
Oh, she took off. I'm just paying the check.

35:55.905 --> 35:58.157
Did you fix her computer?

35:59.242 --> 36:01.494
No, I wasn't really able to.

36:01.577 --> 36:04.789
Because you don't know shit
about fixing computers?

36:12.672 --> 36:14.507
This thing we've been talking about,

36:14.590 --> 36:16.634
- Jerry's thing...
- Yeah?

36:18.427 --> 36:20.930
Secrecy is incredibly important.

36:23.432 --> 36:26.769
I've been working on it for seven months
and you didn't hear about it, right?

36:28.020 --> 36:29.605
- Yeah.
- Okay.

36:30.857 --> 36:32.358
Just be careful when you're drinking.

36:36.279 --> 36:37.697
I will.

36:38.948 --> 36:41.576
- Hey, you ready to go?
- Yeah.

36:43.953 --> 36:45.872
I think you're supposed
to be paying the check.

36:45.955 --> 36:47.707
She's all covered.

36:53.838 --> 36:54.881
MALE HOST: And you were
a high school athlete.

36:54.964 --> 36:56.007
That's right.

36:56.090 --> 36:57.675
There's another thing
we didn't know about you.

36:57.758 --> 37:00.052
Baseball and football.
Pitcher and quarterback.

37:00.136 --> 37:02.930
- It was a small school.
- The question is were you any good?

37:03.014 --> 37:06.601
- I wasn't bad.
- Well, we're gonna find out right now.

37:06.684 --> 37:07.810
- Uh-oh.
- (FEMALE HOST LAUGHING)

37:08.269 --> 37:11.731
We're gonna have you stand on this line
and make five throws.

37:11.814 --> 37:14.609
Every throw that goes
through the tire is $1,000

37:14.692 --> 37:16.569
to the Sloan-Kettering
Memorial Cancer Research Center.

37:16.652 --> 37:17.904
It seems like cancer research

37:17.987 --> 37:19.572
shouldn't have to depend
on my throwing accuracy.

37:19.655 --> 37:21.991
- Come on now, don't chicken out, McAvoy.
- All right.

37:22.074 --> 37:25.161
Wait, there's one more piece of apparatus.

37:25.244 --> 37:26.996
I don't think I'm gonna need a helmet,

37:27.121 --> 37:28.497
- unless you guys plan on...
- Oh, it's just for fun.

37:28.623 --> 37:30.583
FEMALE HOST: It's a morning show.
We have fun here.

37:30.666 --> 37:32.668
- Yeah, all right.
- There it is.

37:32.793 --> 37:34.253
All right, this is for cancer research.

37:34.337 --> 37:36.172
On the line.

37:36.255 --> 37:37.882
On your mark. Get...

37:43.512 --> 37:46.849
I know you think it went badly, but it didn't.

37:46.933 --> 37:48.059
I have to do two things...

37:48.142 --> 37:50.144
I have to write a huge check
to Sloan-Kettering

37:50.227 --> 37:52.188
and then I absolutely
have to break up with you.

37:52.271 --> 37:54.774
They're both important.
I get why the first one has to come first,

37:54.857 --> 37:58.110
but the second one
has to come right after, no delay.

37:58.194 --> 38:01.948
Why didn't you just say
I shouldn't worry about the number?

38:02.031 --> 38:03.616
Because you should.

38:03.699 --> 38:06.702
I was aiming for the fucking light tree.

38:10.373 --> 38:12.208
You didn't care
that you scored in the high 90s

38:12.291 --> 38:14.418
in trust and intelligence?

38:15.461 --> 38:18.422
- You looked like Dukakis riding in the tank.
